# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: meson-build
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:meson-build/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:meson-build/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:meson-build/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Meson is written in Python and runs on Unix-like (including Linux and macOS), Windows and other operating systems.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] It supports building C, C++, C#, CUDA, Objective-C, D, Fortran, Java, Rust, and Vala.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] It handles dependencies via a mechanism named *Wrap*.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] It supports GNU Compiler Collection (gcc), Clang, Visual C++ and other compilers, including non-traditional compilers such as Emscripten and Cython.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] The project uses ninja as the primary backend buildsystem, but can also use Visual Studio or Xcode backends.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Meson's support for Fortran and Cython was improved to help various scientific projects in their switch from setuptools to Meson, for example SciPy.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Meson can be used as a PEP517 backend to build Python *wheels*, via the meson-python package.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] The syntax of Meson's build description files, the Meson language, borrows from Python, but is not Python.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] It is designed such that it can be reimplemented in any other language; for example, muon is a C implementation, and Meson++ is a C++ implementation.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] The dependency on Python is an implementation detail.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] The Meson language is intentionally not Turing-complete, and therefore can not express an arbitrary program.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Instead, arbitrary build steps beyond compiling supported languages can be represented as custom targets.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] The Meson language is strongly typed, such that builtin types like library, executable, string, and lists thereof, are non-interchangeable.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] In particular, unlike Make, the list type does not split strings on whitespace.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Thus, whitespace and other characters in filenames and program arguments are handled cleanly.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] As with any typical buildsystem, correct incremental builds are the most significant speed feature (because all incremental progress is discarded whenever the user is forced to do a clean build).
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Unlike bare Make, the separate configure step ensures that changes to arguments, environment variables and command output are not partially applied in subsequent builds, which would lead to a stale build.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Like Ninja, Meson does not support globbing of source files.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] By requiring all source files to be listed in the build definition files, the build definition file timestamps are sufficient to determine whether the set of source files has changed, thereby ensuring that removed source files are detected.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] CMake supports globbing, but recommends against it for the same reason.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Meson uses ccache automatically if installed.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] It also detects changes to symbol tables of shared libraries to skip relinking executables against the library when there are no ABI changes.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Precompiled headers are supported, but require configuration.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Debug builds are without optimization by default.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] A stated goal of Meson is to facilitate modern development practices.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] As such, Meson knows how to do unity builds, build with test coverage etc. without the programmer having to write support for this.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Meson can automatically find and use external dependencies installed on the user's system via pkg-config, CMake, and project-specific lookups.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Alternatively, or as a fallback, a dependency can be provided as a *subproject* – a Meson project within another, either contained or as a download link, possibly with patches.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] This lets Meson resolve dependency hell for the convenience of casual users who want to compile the project, but may contribute to software bloat if a common installed dependency could have been used instead.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] The mode favored by Linux packagers is therefore fallback.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Meson supports Meson and CMake subprojects.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] A Meson build file may also refer to the WrapDB service.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Cross compilation requires extra configuration, which Meson supports in the form of a separate *cross file*, which can be external to the Meson project.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Setting the library installation directory on x86_64 Unix is handled automatically by Meson, but not by other tools such as Autotools.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] GNOME has made it a goal to port its projects to Meson.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] As of late 2017, GNOME Shell itself exclusively requires Meson after abandoning Autotools, and central components like GTK+, Clutter-GTK, GLib and GStreamer can be built with Meson.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Many freedesktop.org projects have switched to Meson.
[src:meson-build/meson-software] Systemd relies on Meson since dropping Autotools in version 234, and also X.Org and Mesa were ported to Meson.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] Meson has been designed to be as simple to use as possible.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] This page outlines the initial steps needed for installation, troubleshooting, and standard use.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] For more advanced configuration please refer to the command line help `meson --help` or the Meson documentation located at the Mesonbuild website.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] This is the best way to receive the most up-to-date version of Mesonbuild.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] Meson can be run directly from the cloned git repository.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] The most common use case of Meson is compiling code on a code base you are working on.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] The only thing to note is that you need to create a separate build directory.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] Meson will not allow you to build source code inside your source tree.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] All build artifacts are stored in the build directory.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] This allows you to have multiple build trees with different configurations at the same time.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] This way generated files are not added into revision control by accident.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] To recompile after code changes, just type `meson compile`.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] You can do arbitrary changes to source code and build system files and Meson will detect those and will do the right thing.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] If you want to build optimized binaries, just use the argument `--buildtype=debugoptimized` when running Meson.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] It is recommended that you keep one build directory for unoptimized builds and one for optimized ones.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] To compile any given configuration, just go into the corresponding build directory and run `meson compile`.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] Meson will automatically add compiler flags to enable debug information and compiler warnings (i.e.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] This means the user does not have to deal with them and can instead focus on coding.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] Distro packagers usually want total control on the build flags used.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] The commands needed to build and install Meson projects are the following.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] The command line switch `--buildtype=plain` tells Meson not to add its own flags to the command line.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] This gives the packager total control on used flags.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] This is very similar to other build systems.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] The only difference is that the `DESTDIR` variable is passed as an environment variable rather than as an argument to `meson install`.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] As distro builds happen always from scratch, you might consider enabling unity builds on your packages because they are faster and produce better code.
[src:meson-build/quick-guide] However there are many projects that do not build with unity builds enabled so the decision to use unity builds must be done by the packager on a case by case basis.
[src:meson-build/reference-manual] This is the root page of the online Meson reference manual.
[src:meson-build/reference-manual] This manual is also available in a more machine readable format as a JSON documented attached to every release since *0.60.0*.
[src:meson-build/reference-manual] See our IDE integration documentation for more information.
[src:meson-build/reference-manual] The following functions are available in build files.
[src:meson-build/reference-manual] Click on each to see the description and usage.
[src:meson-build/reference-manual] The objects returned by them are listed here.
[src:meson-build/reference-manual] These are built-in objects that are always available.
[src:meson-build/reference-manual] These are objects that can be returned by functions or other methods.
[src:meson-build/software-build] A **software build** is the process of converting source code files into standalone software artifact(s) that can be run on a computer, or the result of doing so.
[src:meson-build/software-build] In include functions such as version control, code quality analysis, compilation, and linking.
[src:meson-build/software-build] In software production, builds optimize software for performance and distribution, packaging into formats such as '.*exe'; '.deb'; '.apk'*.
[src:meson-build/software-build] The build process often employs specialized tools such as CMake, Make, or Gradle, and integrates with automation systems including Jenkins or GitHub Actions.
[src:meson-build/software-build] Despite advancements, challenges such as dependency conflicts, platform compatibility, and long compile times, remain problems.
[src:meson-build/software-build] In software development, building software is an end-to-end process that involves many distinct functions.
[src:meson-build/software-build] Some of these functions are described below.
[src:meson-build/software-build] The version control function carries out activities such as workspace creation and updating, baselining and reporting.
[src:meson-build/software-build] It creates an environment for the build process to run in and captures metadata about the inputs and output of the build process to ensure repeatability and reliability.
[src:meson-build/software-build] Tools such as Git, AccuRev or StarTeam help with these tasks by offering tools to tag specific points in history as being important, and more.
[src:meson-build/software-build] Also known as static program analysis/static code analysis this function is responsible for checking that developers have adhered to the seven axes of code quality: comments, unit tests, duplication, complexity, coding rules, potential bugs and architecture & design.
[src:meson-build/software-build] Ensuring a project has high-quality code results in fewer bugs and influences nonfunctional requirements such as maintainability, extensibility and readability; which have a direct impact on the ROI for a business.
[src:meson-build/software-build] This is only a small feature of managing the build process.
[src:meson-build/software-build] The compilation function turns source files into directly executable or intermediate objects.
[src:meson-build/software-build] Not every project will require this function.
[src:meson-build/software-build] While for simple programs the process consists of a single file being compiled, for complex software the source code may consist of many files and may be combined in different ways to produce many different versions.
[src:meson-build/software-build] A linker or link editor is a computer program that combines intermediate software build files such as object and library files into a single executable file such as a program or library.
[src:meson-build/software-build] A linker is often part of a toolchain that includes a compiler and/or assembler that generates intermediate files that the linker processes.
[src:meson-build/software-build] The linker may be integrated with other toolchain tools such that the user does not interact with the linker directly.
[src:meson-build/software-build] A simpler version that writes its output directly to memory is called the *loader*, though loading is typically considered a separate process.
[src:meson-build/software-build] The process of building a computer program is usually managed by a build tool, a program that coordinates and controls other programs.
[src:meson-build/software-build] Examples of such a program are make, Gradle, Ant, Maven, Rake, SCons and Phing.
[src:meson-build/software-build] The build utility typically needs to compile the various files, in the correct order.
[src:meson-build/software-build] If the source code in a particular file has not changed then it may not need to be recompiled ("may not" rather than "need not" because it may itself depend on other files that have changed).
[src:meson-build/software-build] Sophisticated build utilities and linkers attempt to refrain from recompiling code that does not need it, to shorten the time required to complete the build.
[src:meson-build/software-build] A more complex process may involve other programs producing code or data as part of the build process and software.
[src:meson-build/syntax] The syntax of Meson's specification language has been kept as simple as possible.
[src:meson-build/syntax] It is *strongly typed* so no object is ever converted to another under the covers.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Variables have no visible type which makes Meson *dynamically typed* (also known as *duck typed*).
[src:meson-build/syntax] The main building blocks of the language are *variables*, *numbers*, *booleans*, *strings*, *arrays*, *function calls*, *method calls*, *if statements* and *includes*.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Usually one Meson statement takes just one line.
[src:meson-build/syntax] There is no way to have multiple statements on one line as in e.g.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Function and method calls' argument lists can be split over multiple lines.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Meson will autodetect this case and do the right thing.
[src:meson-build/syntax] In other cases, *(added 0.50)* you can get multi-line statements by ending the line with a `\`.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Apart from line ending whitespace has no syntactic meaning.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Variables in Meson work just like in other high level programming languages.
[src:meson-build/syntax] A variable can contain a value of any type, such as an integer or a string.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Variables don't need to be predeclared, you can just assign to them and they appear.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Here's how you would assign values to two different variables.
[src:meson-build/syntax] One important difference in how variables work in Meson is that all objects are immutable.
[src:meson-build/syntax] When you see an operation which appears like a mutation, actually a new object is created and assigned to the name.
[src:meson-build/syntax] This is different from, for example, how Python works for objects, but similar to e.g.
[src:meson-build/syntax] They are declared simply by writing them out.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Basic arithmetic operations are supported.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Strings in Meson are declared with single quotes.
[src:meson-build/syntax] As in python and C, up to three octal digits are accepted in `\ooo`.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Unrecognized escape sequences are left in the string unchanged, i.e., the backslash is left in the string.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Strings can be concatenated to form a new string using the `+` symbol.
[src:meson-build/syntax] You can concatenate any two strings using `/` as an operator to build paths.
[src:meson-build/syntax] This will always use `/` as the path separator on all platforms.
[src:meson-build/syntax] If any one of the individual segments is an absolute path, all segments before it are dropped.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Note that this is equivalent to using `join_paths()`, which was obsoleted by this operator.
[src:meson-build/syntax] These are raw strings that do not support the escape sequences listed above.
[src:meson-build/syntax] These strings can also be combined with the string formatting functionality via `.format()` described below.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Note that multiline f-string support was added in version 0.63.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Strings support the indexing (`[<num>]`) operator.
[src:meson-build/syntax] This operator allows (read only) accessing a specific character.
[src:meson-build/syntax] The returned value is guaranteed to be a string of length 1.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Strings can be built using the string formatting functionality.
[src:meson-build/syntax] As can be seen, the formatting works by replacing placeholders of type `@number@` with the corresponding argument.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Format strings can be used as a non-positional alternative to the string formatting functionality described above.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Currently only identity-expressions are supported inside of format strings, meaning you cannot use arbitrary Meson expressions inside of them.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Strings also support a number of other methods that return transformed copies.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Since 0.58.0, you can replace a substring from a string.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Since 0.43.0, you can specify one positional string argument, and all characters in that string will be stripped.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Since 0.56.0, you can extract a substring from a string.
[src:meson-build/syntax] The method accepts negative values where negative `start` is relative to the end of string `len(string) - start` as well as negative `end`.
[src:meson-build/syntax] It is best to be unambiguous and specify the full revision level to compare.
[src:meson-build/syntax] An array can contain an arbitrary number of objects of any type.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Note appending to an array will always create a new array object and assign it to `my_array` instead of modifying the original since all objects in Meson are immutable.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Dictionaries are delimited by curly braces.
[src:meson-build/syntax] A dictionary can contain an arbitrary number of key: value pairs.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Keys are required to be strings, but values can be objects of any type.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Prior to *0.53.0* keys were required to be literal strings, i.e., you could not use a variable containing a string value as a key.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Dictionaries are immutable and do not have a guaranteed order.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Dictionaries are available since 0.47.0.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Visit the `dict` objects page in the Reference Manual to read about the methods exposed by dictionaries.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Meson provides a set of usable functions.
[src:meson-build/syntax] The most common use case is creating build objects.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Starting with version 0.49.0 keyword arguments can be specified dynamically.
[src:meson-build/syntax] This is done by passing dictionary representing the keywords to set in the `kwargs` keyword.
[src:meson-build/syntax] A single function can take keyword arguments both directly in the function call and indirectly via the `kwargs` keyword argument.
[src:meson-build/syntax] The only limitation is that it is a hard error to pass any particular key both as a direct and indirect argument.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Attempting to do this causes Meson to immediately exit with an error.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Argument flattening is a Meson feature that aims to simplify using methods and functions.
[src:meson-build/syntax] For functions where this feature is active, Meson takes the list of arguments and flattens all nested lists into one big list.
[src:meson-build/syntax] This code is currently accepted because argument flattening *currently* happens before the parameters are evaluated.
[src:meson-build/syntax] "Support" for such constructs will likely be removed in future Meson releases!
[src:meson-build/syntax] Argument flattening is supported by *most* but not *all* Meson functions and methods.
[src:meson-build/syntax] As a general rule, it can be assumed that a function or method supports argument flattening if the exact list structure is irrelevant to a function.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Whether a function supports argument flattening is documented in the Reference Manual.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Objects can have methods, which are called with the dot operator.
[src:meson-build/syntax] The exact methods it provides depends on the object.
[src:meson-build/syntax] If statements work just like in other languages.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Meson has the standard range of logical operations which can be used in `if` statements.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Logical operations work only on boolean values.
[src:meson-build/syntax] To do an operation on all elements of an iterable, use the `foreach` command.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Here's an example of how you could define two executables with corresponding tests using arrays and foreach.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Here's an example of you could iterate a set of components that should be compiled in according to some configuration.
[src:meson-build/syntax] This uses a dictionary, which is available since 0.47.0.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Since 0.49.0 `break` and `continue` keywords can be used inside foreach loops.
[src:meson-build/syntax] A comment starts with the `#` character and extends until the end of the line.
[src:meson-build/syntax] The ternary operator works just like in other languages.
[src:meson-build/syntax] The only exception is that nested ternary operators are forbidden to improve legibility.
[src:meson-build/syntax] If your branching needs are more complex than this you need to write an `if/else` construct.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Most source trees have multiple subdirectories to process.
[src:meson-build/syntax] These can be handled by Meson's `subdir` command.
[src:meson-build/syntax] It changes to the given subdirectory and executes the contents of `meson.build` in that subdirectory.
[src:meson-build/syntax] All state (variables etc) are passed to and from the subdirectory.
[src:meson-build/syntax] The effect is roughly the same as if the contents of the subdirectory's Meson file would have been written where the include command is.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Meson does not currently support user-defined functions or methods.
[src:meson-build/syntax] The addition of user-defined functions would make Meson Turing-complete which would make it harder to reason about and more difficult to integrate with tools like IDEs.
[src:meson-build/syntax] If because of this limitation you find yourself copying and pasting code a lot you may be able to use a `foreach` loop instead.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Meson is very actively developed and continuously improved.
[src:meson-build/syntax] There is a possibility that future enhancements to the Meson build system will require changes to the syntax.
[src:meson-build/syntax] Such changes might be the addition of new reserved keywords, changing the meaning of existing keywords or additions around the basic building blocks like statements and fundamental types.
[src:meson-build/syntax] It is planned to stabilize the syntax with the 1.0 release.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] This page shows from the ground up how to create a Meson build definition for a simple project.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Then we expand it to use external dependencies to show how easily they can be integrated into your project.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] This tutorial has been written mostly for Linux usage.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] It assumes that you have GTK development libraries available on the system.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] In addition, it is recommended to have the glib library with version 2.74 or higher.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] It is possible to build the GUI application on other platforms, such as Windows and macOS, but you need to install the needed dependencies.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Let's start with the most basic of programs, the classic hello example.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] First we create a file `main.c` which holds the source.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Then we create a Meson build description and put it in a file called `meson.build` in the same directory.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Note that unlike Autotools you do not need to add any source headers to the list of sources.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] We are now ready to build our application.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] First we need to initialize the build by going into the source directory and issuing the following commands.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] We create a separate build directory to hold all of the compiler output.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Meson is different from some other build systems in that it does not permit in-source builds.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] You must always create a separate build directory.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Common convention is to put the default build directory in a subdirectory of your top level source directory.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] When Meson is run it prints the following output.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] For the rest of this document we are going to use the latter form.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Once the executable is built we can run it.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Just printing text is a bit old fashioned.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Let's update our program to create a graphical window instead.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] First we edit the main file to use GTK+.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Then we edit the Meson file, instructing it to find and use the GTK+ libraries.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] We don't need it for the current example.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] The thing to notice is that we do *not* need to recreate our build directory, run any sort of magical commands or the like.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Instead we just type the exact same command as if we were rebuilding our code without any build system changes.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Once you have set up your build directory the first time, you don't ever need to run the `meson` command again.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Meson will automatically detect when you have done changes to build definitions and will take care of everything so users don't have to care.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] In this case the following output is produced.
[src:meson-build/tutorial] Note how Meson noticed that the build definition has changed and reran itself automatically.
